Malaysia Stocks: Lafarge, Malaysia Marine, Tenaga, Padini

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-05-31T09:07:20Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/malaysia-stocks-malaysia-airports-eastern-tenaga-padini.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  Malaysia  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. close in  Kuala
Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 15.45 points, or 1
percent, to 1,558.29, its biggest gain since March 4. The gauge
gained 1.5 percent this month.  Lafarge Malayan Cement Bhd. (LMC)  , Malaysia’s biggest
cement maker, dropped 4 percent to 7.19 ringgit, its largest
decline since Dec. 30, after the government raised gas and
electricity prices. Steel and cement stocks will be hurt the
most from higher energy costs, Goh Yin Foo, a Kuala Lumpur-based
analyst at HwangDBS Vickers Research Sdn., wrote in a report
today.  Malaysia Marine and Heavy Engineering Bhd. (MMHE MK) rose
3.8 percent to 7.75 ringgit, a record close ahead of its
inclusion into the MSCI Malaysia Index. The changes will take
place at the end of today, MSCI Inc. said in a May 16 statement
on its website.  Tenaga Nasional Bhd. (TNB)  , Malaysia’s biggest power
utility, surged 9.1 percent to 7.11 ringgit, the most since
Sept. 19, 2008, after winning government approval to raise
electricity charges by an average 7.1 percent starting June 1.        Padini Holdings Bhd. (PAD)  , a garment maker and
retailer, rose 1.9 percent to 1.10 ringgit, the biggest increase
since May 11, after third-quarter profit climbed 41 percent to
24.4 million ringgit ($8.1 million).  To contact the reporter on this story:
Chan Tien Hin in Kuala Lumpur at 
